<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="499" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,429]" pageId="8" pageNumber="499">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,332,357]" pageId="8" pageNumber="499">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[340,584,332,357]" class="Gastropoda" family="Strombidae" genus="Laevistrombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="8" pageNumber="499" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="guidoi">
<emphasis box="[340,584,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="499">Laevistrombus guidoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is consistently white in colour, with only rare examples showing a pattern similar to the typical 
<emphasis box="[401,582,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="499">
<taxonomicName box="[401,578,367,392]" class="Gastropoda" family="Strombidae" genus="Laevistrombus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="8" pageNumber="499" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="vanikorensis">L. vanikorensis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
The extension of the outer lip callosity and level of “metal like gloss” is highly variable and dependent on the age of the animal’s shell: older animals have greater callosity and more gloss.
</paragraph>
